WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.640
Hey everybody, my name is Michael Chow, and I'm joined with Rich Iannin as we do this

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:08.760
little tiny workshop on Great Tables.

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:13.360
So just a little bit about us, we're software engineers at PositPBC.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:20.040
Collectively we have two PhDs, two dogs, and five cats, and we're total fanatics about

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:21.120
table display.

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:26.639
So in this workshop, the way it's set up is we'll alternate between slides and a code

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:27.639
along.

00:00:27.639 --> 00:00:32.439
So in the slides, we'll give you a basic understanding of simple Great Tables concepts and functions.

00:00:32.439 --> 00:00:35.840
In the code along, we'll code through some different tables so you can see how they're

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:39.320
made and get some practice in making tables.

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:44.439
And the workshop materials are online, so you can find them on GitHub, on Rich Iannin,

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:46.480
Great Tables mini-workshop.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:52.759
And if you have any questions, we have a Great Tables Discord, so we'd love to have you join,

00:00:52.759 --> 00:00:57.500
and it's super helpful when people ask questions about Great Tables.

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:03.660
So the big question with display tables is, what is a display table?

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:10.220
So essentially, Great Tables is a Python library for creating publication-ready tables.

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:15.379
And what we mean by that is less like the table on the left, which is a raw Polars data

00:01:15.379 --> 00:01:23.980
frame, and more like the table on the right, which is a formatted, styled, beautified table

00:01:23.980 --> 00:01:26.099
that you might put in a report.

00:01:26.099 --> 00:01:30.680
And the big reason is the table on the left is really useful if you're doing data analysis.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:33.080
You really want to know the names of your columns.

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:35.180
You want to see all of your data.

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:39.220
But the table on the right's really useful when you want to hand it off to someone and

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:43.900
to publish insights and try to spur people to action.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:46.699
So Great Tables is all about the table on the right.

00:01:46.699 --> 00:01:48.839
All right.

00:01:48.839 --> 00:01:52.779
So I'm going to go through some really nice display tables that we found on the internet

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:59.220
to just try to highlight some of the value of publishing tables and formatting them

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:01.339
nicely for presentation.

00:02:01.339 --> 00:02:04.580
So here's one about a basketball team.

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:08.419
So history does not bode well for the Hoosiers.

00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:10.220
This is about a specific team.

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:12.880
The thing I want to emphasize here is a few pieces.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:18.899
We have a heading, which lets you put a title and some high-level information.

00:02:18.899 --> 00:02:23.860
We have a spanner, which groups columns together with a high-level label.

00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:29.139
We have these team logos for conveying each team really quickly.

00:02:29.139 --> 00:02:31.179
And then we can also highlight rows.

00:02:31.179 --> 00:02:36.020
So this row is the topic of this article we found it from, and it's highlighted to draw

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:38.619
attention to the main subject.

00:02:38.619 --> 00:02:42.820
And then we also have these percentage values here.

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:48.220
So notice percentages here are formatted nicely to just be two decimals for people.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:53.300
So this is a really good-looking table, and it's a nice way to communicate information

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:54.539
clearly.

00:02:54.539 --> 00:02:56.220
It's got a little bit of emphasis.

00:02:56.220 --> 00:03:00.940
It's got some labels and a lot of nice pieces for presentation.

00:03:00.940 --> 00:03:02.740
All right.

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:03.740
Here's another one.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:07.259
So this is about a specific basketball player.

00:03:07.259 --> 00:03:12.179
So this table, some nice things about it are it has bar charts.

00:03:12.539 --> 00:03:16.899
So you can actually include small graphics in your table.

00:03:16.899 --> 00:03:19.259
It also has the rows split up.

00:03:19.259 --> 00:03:22.699
So there's some grouping behind the rows.

00:03:22.699 --> 00:03:27.300
And then the last thing is it has these footnotes here for providing additional details.

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:36.000
All right, and the last table to show you is this table that's CO2 intensity and power

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.500
consumption by country.

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:46.220
So notice this has countries ordered by their CO2 intensity, and then it has them the percentage

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:50.020
of different power sources that they consume.

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:54.779
And notice the use of color here, that this table is able to code more green sources of

00:03:54.779 --> 00:04:01.539
power against dirtier sources of power here.

00:04:01.539 --> 00:04:06.460
And we're able to see through this heat map trends that countries that tend to have low

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:10.380
CO2 intensity tend to use cleaner sources.

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:16.820
So this is a really neat way that tables can provide sort of heat map information to people.

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:22.940
We have nicely formatted percentage values and then a heat map here to make it easier

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:24.579
to pull out patterns.

00:04:24.579 --> 00:04:26.119
All right.

00:04:26.119 --> 00:04:30.540
So these three tables are made from code.

00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:35.579
And that's part of the powers that you can basically maintain a reproducible workflow

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:42.500
in Python, where you take data from input to reporting all with Python code.

00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:44.220
A big question is how did we get here?

00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:50.019
So this was mostly the work of Rich Ianan in figuring out how to generate the right

00:04:50.019 --> 00:04:52.660
API for creating display tables.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.980
As it turns out, there are a lot of books on data analysis and plotting, but it's a

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:00.739
lot harder to find books on table design.

00:05:00.899 --> 00:05:06.540
One book in particular stood out, and this is the Census Manual of Tabular Presentation.

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:14.339
It's a pretty old book, but it contains basically tons of concepts on how to display tables

00:05:14.339 --> 00:05:18.980
and a lot of really useful recommendations on creating tables.

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:21.820
So this was published way back in 1949.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:25.540
But as it turns out, it's super relevant even today.

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:30.660
So here's an example about how to formalize the structure of a table and different parts

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:35.299
of a table and even names you might give to them.

00:05:35.299 --> 00:05:37.820
And that's exactly what we used today.

00:05:37.820 --> 00:05:45.019
So here we have this modern take on the table display framework that powers great tables.

00:05:45.019 --> 00:05:48.660
So notice we have parts like a header with a title and subtitle.

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:54.859
We have column labels with something called a spanner label, which is high-level columns.

00:05:54.859 --> 00:06:00.019
And then we have everything in the table body and source notes.

00:06:00.019 --> 00:06:02.739
So a lot of different pieces of the table put together here.

00:06:02.739 --> 00:06:07.260
And the hope of this graphic is just to provide an easy way to get a sense for the pieces

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:08.260
of a table.

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:10.779
So a big question is, how do you make tables today?

00:06:10.779 --> 00:06:16.179
So if you have this raw table, the big question is, what do you do to take it from this raw

00:06:16.179 --> 00:06:18.380
input to display?

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:24.140
You could show this table to people, but it's not the cleanest to read or to pull things

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:26.220
out of.

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:29.660
A really common workflow we see is Excel.

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:35.299
You could instead copy your data out into Excel to make a nice-looking table.

00:06:35.299 --> 00:06:40.339
But the big challenge here is now that you have a broken workflow, and it can be hard

00:06:40.339 --> 00:06:42.540
to reproduce.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:46.820
There could be quirks in Excel that could be hard to capture.

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:51.980
And so essentially, your workflow has broken.

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:55.920
With great tables, you can do everything entirely in Python.

00:06:55.920 --> 00:07:00.559
So you can have a nice, reproducible Python workflow from beginning to end.

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:02.000
All right.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:07.880
So to recap, great tables is a package focused purely on displaying tables.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:11.600
It's not the only approach you can use out there in Python, but we've tried to make it

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.399
comprehensive.

00:07:13.399 --> 00:07:15.480
We develop it actively.

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:21.399
And we've tried to really capture a really wide range of table problems out there.

00:07:21.399 --> 00:07:23.239
All right.

00:07:23.239 --> 00:07:29.239
So this workshop is to help you learn the process and design behind making presentation-quality

00:07:29.239 --> 00:07:31.559
tables.

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:37.820
So in this first part, I'm going to talk a bit about structure, formatting, and styling.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:43.279
So to go through, we're going to use this example table that we'll call the coffee table.

00:07:43.279 --> 00:07:46.519
And we're going to walk through its different pieces.

00:07:46.519 --> 00:07:50.839
So this table is mostly made of three pieces, structure, format, and style.

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:56.000
And the structure pieces are pieces like the title, these column spanners, which go

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:01.000
over our column labels, and then cleaning up the column labels themselves.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:07.640
For format, we have things like formatting currency values, for example, to put a dollar

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:11.839
sign and commas in the right place, and percentages.

00:08:11.839 --> 00:08:15.160
So notice the percentages here are whole values.

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:17.679
So we just clean them up a little bit for presentation.

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:18.679
All right.

00:08:18.679 --> 00:08:20.320
And the last piece is styling.

00:08:20.799 --> 00:08:24.679
So notice that we've filled the color for some of these rows.

00:08:24.679 --> 00:08:30.799
So all the revenue columns are Alice Blue, and all the profit columns are Papaya Whip.

00:08:30.799 --> 00:08:35.440
The other thing we did is we bolded the text on the bottom row so that it's a little bit

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:40.000
easier to see that it's totaling everything, and it's a little bit different from the other

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.059
rows of the table.

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:46.000
So that's the basics of structuring, formatting, and styling.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.919
So let's talk a little bit about setup, because there are a couple pieces before we go into

00:08:50.919 --> 00:08:53.840
the code used to create tables like that.

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.020
There's a couple pieces to get out of the way.

00:08:56.020 --> 00:09:01.359
So the first is Great Tables works really well with Polars.

00:09:01.359 --> 00:09:06.080
And if you've never used Polars, Polars is a data frame library for Python that's really

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:11.760
taking off and has a lot of really nice, a really good API design that makes it easy

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:13.520
to work with.

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:19.960
Great Tables also works with Pandas, but we'll use Polars for all our examples in our code.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:24.280
And one thing you need to know is that Polars has a neat concept called selectors.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:28.679
These make it easy to select columns of data using a really convenient syntax.

00:09:28.679 --> 00:09:34.400
So here we import Polar selectors, and we can say something like starts with revenue,

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:38.280
and that will select all the revenue columns of our data.

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:43.239
This will be really useful because we'll use this a lot in Great Tables to, for example,

00:09:43.239 --> 00:09:48.760
put labels over columns or to grab columns to format in our table.

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:54.239
So with that out of the way, I'm going to go into the basics of structuring tables.

00:09:54.239 --> 00:09:58.039
So what we're going to do is we're going to use this example table from Great Tables called

00:09:58.039 --> 00:10:02.840
Exible to show off all the pieces that I walked through before, the structuring, formatting

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:04.340
and styling.

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:12.280
So to get this table, we import Exible from Great Tables and this class GT, which is the

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:16.599
class that powers all of the Great Tables fun.

00:10:16.599 --> 00:10:18.159
All right.

00:10:18.159 --> 00:10:24.159
So this is when we call GT over Exible, we just get this really basic table with really

00:10:24.159 --> 00:10:27.559
simple formatting to start out.

00:10:27.559 --> 00:10:29.640
All right.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:32.679
So let's go through first making row labels.

00:10:32.679 --> 00:10:37.599
So we have these row names in this column called row.

00:10:37.599 --> 00:10:45.320
And what we can do is we can use the simple argument row name call to sort of set the

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:47.280
row on its own.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:49.400
So this is called the stub.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:54.719
And this sort of just creates a divide between the rows and the table.

00:10:54.719 --> 00:10:59.880
This is useful for adding a little bit of emphasis to row names.

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:01.760
All right.

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:03.880
So that's a really simple activity.

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:06.799
Another one is that we can make row groups.

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:09.840
So we have this group column right here.

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:15.320
And we can do that simply by adding another argument group name call with the column name

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:16.960
for our groups.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:24.239
And then notice that that will create these sort of horizontal rows that mark each group.

00:11:24.239 --> 00:11:27.119
So now our groups are sort of marked from each other.

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:32.799
And this makes it really easy to sort of group rows and split them up.

00:11:32.799 --> 00:11:36.640
So it's easy to see which rows belong together.

00:11:37.479 --> 00:11:42.520
So just to compare the table we started with and the one with a stub and row groups, notice

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:48.359
the basic GT table is on the left and the sort of gussied up one we made is on the right

00:11:48.359 --> 00:11:51.380
with row groups and a stub.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:54.760
So the next thing you might want to do is add a title to your table.

00:11:54.760 --> 00:12:00.159
So to add a title, what we'll do is we'll just use this really simple tab header method

00:12:00.159 --> 00:12:02.020
with the title argument.

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:07.219
So notice we've added the title table title right here.

00:12:07.219 --> 00:12:09.140
So pretty easy.

00:12:09.140 --> 00:12:14.799
You can also add subtitles by adding the subtitle argument to tab header.

00:12:14.799 --> 00:12:19.380
So pretty quick, but lets you explain your data a little bit more.

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:24.419
So next up, we're going to add spanners, which are rows above our column labels.

00:12:24.419 --> 00:12:26.900
So to do this, we'll use the tab spanner method.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:29.659
So our key here is we'll pass it two arguments.

00:12:29.659 --> 00:12:33.340
So we're going to pass it the columns argument, which is the columns we want to put a label

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:37.500
above, and then a label argument, which is the label itself.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:42.440
So notice we put the label of spanner above date time and date time.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:46.700
And there it is in the data, just right above our column labels.

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:49.140
The next method is calls label.

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:53.400
So what calls label does is it renames our columns.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:57.619
And this is really nice because in the data, column names often have underscores, they're

00:12:57.619 --> 00:12:59.260
often all lowercase.

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:02.260
So this is a chance to clean up the names.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:08.419
So that's the gist of using things like tab header, tab spanner, and calls label to clean

00:13:08.419 --> 00:13:09.419
things up.

00:13:09.419 --> 00:13:10.419
Okay.

00:13:10.419 --> 00:13:15.700
So in the last section on structure, we looked at creating a stub with row names, creating

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:23.020
groupings of rows, and then adding a simple title with tab header, column labels with

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:24.500
calls label.

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:30.640
And then we use tab spanner to add high level labels over our columns.

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:34.460
In this next section, we're going to go through the basics of formatting.

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:38.780
So how to clean up the values of the data themselves.

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:42.700
And the thing to know is there's a ton of formatting methods in great tables.

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:47.059
So we've really bent over backwards to try to accommodate tons of situations.

00:13:47.059 --> 00:13:52.059
And if you think about it, when people copy their data into Excel, they're using tons

00:13:52.099 --> 00:13:56.820
of formatters in Excel to format dates and percentages and things like that.

00:13:56.820 --> 00:14:04.179
So we've tried to really bring that like essence of Excel formatting into great tables.

00:14:04.179 --> 00:14:07.619
So they all start with FMT for format.

00:14:07.619 --> 00:14:13.539
And there's quite a few around like numbers, integers, currencies, and then a lot of date

00:14:13.539 --> 00:14:15.820
related ones as well.

00:14:15.820 --> 00:14:18.739
So there's a huge variety of methods available.

00:14:18.739 --> 00:14:20.140
Okay.

00:14:20.140 --> 00:14:22.619
So we're going to go through two of them.

00:14:22.619 --> 00:14:24.760
The first one's format currency.

00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:27.260
So this is to format monetary values.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:33.780
So we'll start with this example table again, just to have a base to work from.

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:37.020
And then what we're going to do is we're going to format this currency column here.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:43.020
So notice that it doesn't have dollar signs, and it has three decimals in a lot of places,

00:14:43.020 --> 00:14:45.700
which might not be what we want to represent.

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:46.700
Okay.

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:51.979
So to do that, we're just going to use the format currency method and pass it the currency

00:14:51.979 --> 00:14:53.539
column.

00:14:53.539 --> 00:14:58.739
And what it's going to do is it's going to put a dollar sign in front of currency and

00:14:58.739 --> 00:15:01.380
just use the two decimal places.

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:08.619
Since by default it formats for USD, US currency, but you can also set it to other ones.

00:15:08.619 --> 00:15:10.780
And just to show you, this is the before and after.

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:14.820
So notice the dollar sign and fewer decimals here.

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:18.380
So the next formatter I'm going to look at is format percent.

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:22.580
And this is to format data as percentages.

00:15:22.580 --> 00:15:25.099
So right now we have this value column.

00:15:25.099 --> 00:15:31.780
Sorry, we're going to create this data to show off format percentage since it's a little

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:35.780
hard to show off in Exible, but these kinds of problems show up a lot.

00:15:35.780 --> 00:15:40.820
So in this new data we're creating, notice we have these values here that we might want

00:15:40.820 --> 00:15:43.020
to format as percentages.

00:15:43.020 --> 00:15:48.460
So what we do is we just call the format percent method on this value column.

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:55.460
And what we get back is the percentage sign after, and notice the decimals are shifted.

00:15:55.460 --> 00:16:02.179
It basically takes the first two decimal places as percentages.

00:16:02.179 --> 00:16:09.700
So just to show you a little bit closer, notice 0.02 is rendered as 2% here.

00:16:09.700 --> 00:16:13.419
So pretty simple, but makes a big difference when you're doing a lot of reporting.

00:16:13.419 --> 00:16:18.020
So we looked at formatting with two methods.

00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:24.219
Format currency, which lets you say add a dollar sign and clean up the decimals of a

00:16:24.219 --> 00:16:30.979
currency value, and format percent, which lets you render percentages a little bit nicer.

00:16:30.979 --> 00:16:36.979
So with a percentage sign afterwards and treating the decimals like percentages, which is really

00:16:36.979 --> 00:16:39.039
common.

00:16:39.039 --> 00:16:43.400
So with structure and formatting out of the way, we're going to go through styling the

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:46.400
table with a method called tab style.

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:50.359
So tab style is a little bit more complicated than the other things we looked at, but it's

00:16:50.359 --> 00:16:52.020
not too much more difficult.

00:16:52.020 --> 00:16:57.739
It just involves a couple pieces for customizing what we want to style and how.

00:16:57.739 --> 00:17:03.580
So the key is tab style takes two arguments, style and locations.

00:17:03.580 --> 00:17:11.140
And so we use helper functions from great tables to specify these two pieces.

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:16.660
And the key is that style is like the what, and locations is like the where.

00:17:16.660 --> 00:17:19.339
So what kind of styling are we going to use?

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:21.219
Are we going to color the text?

00:17:21.219 --> 00:17:23.079
Are we going to fill the background?

